In general, US high schools and colleges are 4 years long and the names of those four years are the same for both, freshman, sophomore, junior and senior.

@Andrzej

In my experience in both undergraduate and graduate school, nobody identified as "freshman, sophomore, junior, or senior." as Vaer said.  Maybe on the East coast, or in some expensive private colleges, but not in the midwest for people and in colleges where many of the students were first generation college attendees.

I was never referred to as one of these categories, and I never heard of a class being identified as such, either.  Their were beginning and higher level classes.

@Stephen back in my receding youth (this would be early '80s), the math curriculum had a class specifically called "geometry" in 9th or 10th grade (ages 14-15 for the non-Americans). This was between "Algebra I" (mostly simple linear equations) and "Algebra II" (quadratics and trig).

A portion of the curriculum was devoted to fairly simple geometric proofs, usually along the lines of showing that some line segment AB in a diagram was congruent to line segment CD. We were trained to conclude these proofs with "QED."

We might have done similar simpler proofs back in 5th or 6th grade (ages 9-10).

